`crates/ctx-brief/src` is the whole `ctx-brief` binary: turn a `docs/STATUS.md` backlog item or free-text ask into a self-contained executor brief by running two `claude` CLI passes (read-only gather, then plan) inside the *target* repo so its own context hooks fire. Depending on this crate means depending on `main`/`cli::dispatch`; everything else is internal orchestration.

The trait seams `Fs` (fs.rs) and `Claude` (claude.rs) are what make `runner::run` testable — new logic needing disk or `claude` access must go through them, never `std::fs`/raw process calls directly. `runner.rs` is the hub: it loads fixed-name prompt files from `cfg.prompts_dir`, calls `status_item::resolve` to turn free text into a grounded backlog item (with its silent no-match fallback and `AmbiguousItem` case), then drives gather/plan through `Claude`. `cli.rs` builds `runner::Config` from flags, deriving the output path via `slug()` — the only place that filename logic lives — and distinguishing `out_rel` (repo-relative, used by interactive sessions) from `out_fs` (cwd-relative, used for this process's own write/verify); mixing these breaks either the write or the `BriefError::BriefNotWritten` check. `main.rs` wires real `StdFs`/`ClaudeCli` and handles the `--contract` bypass before `clap` parsing.

`error.rs`'s `BriefError` is the single error surface all of the above must funnel into — no raw `io::Error`/`anyhow` escapes, and any new failure mode gets a variant there. `contract.rs`'s `CONTRACT` string must stay in sync with actual CLI behavior (flags, output path convention, two-stage model) or the `contracts` battery check fails the build — it's documentation with a real assertion behind it. `GATHER_TOOLS` in `runner.rs` and the prompt filenames it loads are the concrete points where changing the two-stage flow requires touching both `runner.rs` and the prompt files on disk (not shown here).